We can recall that the formula for Degree of Operating Leverage (DOL) is given as:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Degree of Operating Leverage }&=1+\dfrac{\text{Fixed Cost}}{\text{Operating Cash Flow}}
\end{aligned}$$

Next, we need to solve for the DOL at the accounting break-even point. We can recall that the accounting break even occurs when the company generates exactly zero profits. This can be solved using the formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Q}&=\dfrac{\text{FC}+\text{D}}{\text{P}-\text{v}}
\end{aligned}$$

Where,

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{FC}&=\text{Fixed cost}\\
\text{D}&=\text{Depreciation}\\
\text{P}&=\text{Price per unit}\\
\text{v}&=\text{Variable cost per unit}
\end{aligned}$$
